# Week 5 — RAID and Motherboards

## RAID

* RAID means Redundant Array of Independent Disks.
* RAID is designed for availability and drive-failure tolerance.
* RAID is not a replacement for a separate backup.

### RAID 0

* Uses striping.
* Data is divided across multiple drives.
* Provides increased performance.
* Provides no redundancy.
* Failure of one drive destroys the entire array.

### RAID 1

* Uses mirroring.
* The same data is written to multiple drives.
* Two 1 TB drives provide 1 TB of usable capacity.
* The array can continue operating after one drive fails.

### RAID 5

* Combines striping with distributed parity.
* Requires at least three drives.
* Can survive one drive failure.
* Uses the equivalent capacity of one drive for parity.

### RAID 6

* Combines striping with double distributed parity.
* Requires at least four drives.
* Can survive two drive failures.
* Uses the equivalent capacity of two drives for parity.
* Five 1 TB drives provide approximately 3 TB usable capacity.

### RAID 10

* Combines RAID 1 and RAID 0.
* Also called a stripe of mirrors.
* Requires at least four drives.
* Can survive multiple drive failures if both drives in the same mirror pair do not fail.

## Motherboard Form Factors

* ATX means Advanced Technology Extended.
* ATX provides the most expansion space of the three main A+ form factors.
* Micro-ATX is smaller and usually has fewer expansion slots.
* Mini-ITX is the smallest and is designed for compact systems.
* Form factor describes physical size, layout, mounting points, and compatibility.

## Expansion Buses

* A computer bus connects motherboard components.
* PCI means Peripheral Component Interconnect.
* PCI uses parallel communication.
* PCIe means Peripheral Component Interconnect Express.
* PCIe uses serial lanes.
* PCIe x1, x4, x8, and x16 describe the number of lanes.
* Modern graphics cards normally use PCIe x16.

## Motherboard Power and Connections

* Older ATX motherboards used a 20-pin main connector.
* Modern ATX motherboards normally use a 24-pin connector.
* The 24-pin connector provides main motherboard power.
* PCIe 6-pin and 8-pin connectors provide additional power to expansion cards.
* A PCIe 6-pin connector supplies up to 75 watts.
* A PCIe 8-pin connector supplies up to 150 watts.
* Front-panel headers connect power buttons, reset buttons, and LEDs.
* USB headers connect front-panel USB ports.
* TPM means Trusted Platform Module.
* M.2 drives are inserted at an angle and secured with a screw or latch.

## CPUs and Server Motherboards

* Intel and AMD processors require compatible sockets and motherboards.
* CPU installation should not require force.
* The CPU must be aligned correctly before locking the retention mechanism.
* Multisocket server motherboards support multiple physical CPUs.
* Server motherboards commonly support more RAM and expansion slots.
* Standard server racks are 19 inches wide.

